Deesha Dyer has been promoted to Special Assistant to the President and Social Secretary at the White House. She was selected for her dedication to opening the doors of the White House to students from across the country. Previously, she worked as Deputy Director and Deputy Social Secretary and has been with the White House since 2009 when she started as an intern. Dyer's new role involves leading the Social Office team and furthering the goals and priorities of the President and First Lady. She has been praised for her passion, creativity, and public-mindedness. Dyer was born in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, and raised in Philadelphia and Hershey. She attended the Milton Hershey School. Prior to her government career, Dyer held positions in the private sector and was involved in community advocacy. She currently volunteers with the homeless community in Washington, DC, and serves as a mentor for a global empowerment program for young girls in Philadelphia.